# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-iceberg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Iceberg was started at Netflix by Ryan Blue and Dan Weeks.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Apache Hive was used by many different services and engines in the Netflix infrastructure.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Hive was never able to guarantee correctness and did not provide stable atomic transactions.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Many at Netflix avoided using these services and making changes to the data to avert unintended consequences from the Hive format.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Improve performance by enabling finer-grained operations to be done at the file granularity for optimal writes.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Simplify and abstract general operation and maintenance of tables.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] The project was open-sourced and donated to the Apache Software Foundation in November 2018.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] In May 2020, the Iceberg project graduated to become a top-level Apache project.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Iceberg is used by multiple companies including Airbnb, Apple, Expedia, LinkedIn, Adobe, Lyft.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Apache Iceberg operates by abstracting table metadata from the underlying data storage.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] It maintains metadata files that track snapshots, schema information, partition layouts, and data file locations, enabling efficient and atomic table operations.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] At a high level, Iceberg organizes table data into snapshots.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Each snapshot represents the state of the table at a particular point in time, allowing Iceberg to provide ACID-compliant transactional capabilities, including snapshot isolation, concurrent writes, and rollback functionality.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] The snapshot metadata is managed as a tree structure of manifest files and metadata files stored within the file system.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Iceberg uses the Apache Parquet file format for storing actual data due to its efficient columnar storage structure, optimized for analytical queries.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Parquet files in Iceberg store table rows in a compressed, column-oriented format, significantly reducing storage costs and improving read performance through techniques such as predicate pushdown and column pruning.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Iceberg references Parquet files in manifest files, facilitating quick identification and access to relevant data during query execution.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Apache Iceberg employs a multi‐level metadata hierarchy for tracking table contents.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] At the top, a table metadata file (often metadata.json) stores table-level information—such as the schema, partition specifications, the list of snapshots, and pointers to the current "root" snapshot.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Each snapshot represents a consistent view of the table and is associated with a manifest list (an Avro file) that enumerates all manifest files for that snapshot.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] A manifest file is an index that lists a set of data files (e.g., Parquet files) along with metadata about each file – including row count, partition values, and column statistics such as minimum and maximum values.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] These manifests are small metadata files (often in Avro format) that segment the table’s metadata, enabling a distributed design whereby entire manifests can be pruned when querying by partition instead of requiring a single, giant file listing all data files.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] Moreover, Iceberg’s metadata tree provides an historic record of table changes—retaining old snapshots and manifests (thus enabling time travel) until they expire—and it can quickly plan queries by reading only the relevant manifest files rather than scanning all data files or directories.
[src:apache-iceberg/apache-iceberg] This approach avoids expensive operations such as directory listing and makes metadata access efficient even for huge tables.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:apache-iceberg/data-lakehouse] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:apache-iceberg/latest] Schema evolution works and won't inadvertently un-delete data.
[src:apache-iceberg/latest] Users don't need to know about partitioning to get fast queries.
[src:apache-iceberg/latest] Iceberg is used in production where a single table can contain tens of petabytes of data and even these huge tables can be read without a distributed SQL engine.
[src:apache-iceberg/latest] Iceberg was designed to solve correctness problems in eventually-consistent cloud object stores.
[src:apache-iceberg/latest] Iceberg has been designed and developed to be an open community standard with a specification to ensure compatibility across languages and implementations.
[src:apache-iceberg/latest] Apache Iceberg is open source, and is developed at the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] A **partition** is a division of a logical database or its constituent elements into distinct independent parts.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Database partitioning refers to intentionally breaking a large database into smaller ones for scalability purposes, distinct from network partitions which are a type of network fault between nodes.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] In a partitioned database, each piece of data belongs to exactly one partition, effectively making each partition a small database of its own.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Database partitioning is normally done for manageability, performance or availability reasons, or for load balancing.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] It is popular in distributed database management systems, where each partition may be spread over multiple nodes, with users at the node performing local transactions on the partition.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] This increases performance for sites that have regular transactions involving certain views of data, whilst maintaining availability and security.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Partitioning enables distribution of datasets across multiple disks and query loads across multiple processors.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] For queries that operate on a single partition, each node executes queries independently on its local partition, enabling linear scaling of query throughput with additional nodes.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] More complex queries can be parallelized across multiple nodes, though this presents additional challenges.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Database partitioning emerged in the 1980s with systems like Teradata and NonStop SQL.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] The approach was later adopted by NoSQL databases and Hadoop-based data warehouses.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] While implementations vary between transactional and analytical workloads, the core principles of partitioning remain consistent across both use cases.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Partitioning is commonly implemented alongside replication, storing partition copies across multiple nodes.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Each record belongs to one partition but may exist on multiple nodes for fault tolerance.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] In leader-follower replication systems, nodes can simultaneously serve as leaders for some partitions and followers for others.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Partitioning aims to distribute data and query load evenly across nodes.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] With ideal distribution, system capacity scales linearly with added nodes—ten nodes should process ten times the data and throughput of a single node.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Uneven distribution, termed *skew*, reduces partitioning efficiency.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Partitions with excessive load are called *hot spots*.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Current high-end relational database management systems provide for different criteria to split the database.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] They take a *partitioning key* and assign a partition based on certain criteria.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] In any partitioning scheme, data is typically arranged so that each piece of data (record, row, or document) belongs to exactly one partition.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] While some databases support operations that span multiple partitions, this single-partition association is fundamental to the partitioning concept.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] The partitioning can be done by either building separate smaller databases (each with its own tables, indices, and transaction logs), or by splitting selected elements, for example just one table.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Horizontal partitioning involves putting different rows into different tables.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] For example, customers with ZIP codes less than 50000 are stored in CustomersEast, while customers with ZIP codes greater than or equal to 50000 are stored in CustomersWest.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] The two partition tables are then CustomersEast and CustomersWest, while a view with a union might be created over both of them to provide a complete view of all customers.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Vertical partitioning involves creating tables with fewer columns and using additional tables to store the remaining columns.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Generally, this practice is known as normalization.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] However, vertical partitioning extends further, and partitions columns even when already normalized.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] This type of partitioning is also called "row splitting", since rows get split by their columns, and might be performed explicitly or implicitly.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Distinct physical machines might be used to realize vertical partitioning: storing infrequently used or very wide columns, taking up a significant amount of memory, on a different machine, for example, is a method of vertical partitioning.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] A common form of vertical partitioning is to split static data from dynamic data, since the former is faster to access than the latter, particularly for a table where the dynamic data is not used as often as the static.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] Creating a view across the two newly created tables restores the original table with a performance penalty, but accessing the static data alone will show higher performance.
[src:apache-iceberg/partition-database] A columnar database can be regarded as a database that has been vertically partitioned until each column is stored in its own table.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] In computer science, **schema versioning** and **schema evolution**, deal with the need to retain current data and software system functionality in the face of changing database structure.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] The problem is not limited to the modification of the schema.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] It, in fact, affects the data stored under the given schema and the queries (and thus the applications) posed on that schema.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] A database design is sometimes created as a "as of now" instance and thus schema evolution is not considered.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] (This is different but related to where a database is designed as a "one size fits all" which doesn't cover attribute volatility).
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] Due to this historical heritage the process of schema evolution as of 2008 a particularly taxing one.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] It is, in fact, widely acknowledged that the data management core of an applications is one of the most difficult and critical components to evolve.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] The key problem is the impact of the schema evolution on queries and applications.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] As shown in the article *Schema Evolution in Wikipedia - Toward a Web Information System Benchmark* (2008) (which provides an analysis of the MediaWiki evolution) each evolution step might affect up to 70% of the queries operating on the schema, that must be manually reworked consequently.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] In 2008, the problem has been recognized as a pressing one by the database community for more than 12 years.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] Supporting schema evolution is a difficult problem involving complex mapping among schema versions and the tool support has been so far very limited.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] The recent theoretical advances on mapping composition and mapping invertibility, which represent the core problems underlying the schema evolution remains almost inaccessible to the large public.
[src:apache-iceberg/schema-evolution] The issue is particular felt by temporal databases.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation has been adopted by several major database management systems, such as InterBase, Firebird, Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Anywhere, MongoDB and Microsoft SQL Server (2005 and later).
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] The main reason for its adoption is that it allows better performance than serializability, yet still avoids most of the concurrency anomalies that serializability avoids (but not all).
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation has been used to criticize the ANSI SQL-92 standard's definition of isolation levels, as it exhibits none of the "anomalies" that the SQL standard prohibited, yet is not serializable (the anomaly-free isolation level defined by ANSI).
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] In spite of its distinction from serializability, snapshot isolation is sometimes referred to as *serializable* by Oracle.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] A transaction executing under snapshot isolation appears to operate on a personal *snapshot* of the database, taken at the start of the transaction.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] When the transaction concludes, it will successfully commit only if the values updated by the transaction have not been changed externally since the snapshot was taken.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Such a write–write conflict will cause the transaction to abort.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] In a *write skew* anomaly, two transactions (T1 and T2) concurrently read an overlapping data set (e.g. values V1 and V2), concurrently make disjoint updates (e.g.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] T1 updates V1, T2 updates V2), and finally concurrently commit, neither having seen the update performed by the other.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Were the system serializable, such an anomaly would be impossible, as either T1 or T2 would have to occur "first", and be visible to the other.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] In contrast, snapshot isolation permits write skew anomalies.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] As a concrete example, imagine V1 and V2 are two balances held by a single person, Phil.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] The bank will allow either V1 or V2 to run a deficit, provided the total held in both is never negative (i.e.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Phil initiates two transactions concurrently, T1 withdrawing $200 from V1, and T2 withdrawing $200 from V2.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] If the database guaranteed serializable transactions, the simplest way of coding T1 is to deduct $200 from V1, and then verify that V1 + V2 ≥ 0 still holds, aborting if not.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] T2 similarly deducts $200 from V2 and then verifies V1 + V2 ≥ 0.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Since the transactions must serialize, either T1 happens first, leaving V1 = −$100, V2 = $100, and preventing T2 from succeeding (since V1 + (V2 − $200) is now −$200), or T2 happens first and similarly prevents T1 from committing.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] If the database is under snapshot isolation(MVCC), however, T1 and T2 operate on private snapshots of the database: each deducts $200 from an account, and then verifies that the new total is zero, using the other account value that held when the snapshot was taken.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Since neither *update* conflicts, both commit successfully, leaving V1 = V2 = −$100, and V1 + V2 = −$200.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Some systems built using multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) may support (only) snapshot isolation to allow transactions to proceed without worrying about concurrent operations, and more importantly without needing to re-verify all read operations when the transaction finally commits.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] This is convenient because MVCC maintains a series of recent history consistent states.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] The only information that must be stored during the transaction is a list of updates made, which can be scanned for conflicts fairly easily before being committed.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] However, MVCC systems (such as MarkLogic) will use locks to serialize writes together with MVCC to obtain some of the performance gains and still support the stronger "serializability" level of isolation.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Potential inconsistency problems arising from write skew anomalies can be fixed by adding (otherwise unnecessary) updates to the transactions in order to enforce the serializability property.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Add a special conflict table, which both transactions update in order to create a direct write–write conflict.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Have one transaction "update" a read-only location (replacing a value with the same value) in order to create a direct write–write conflict (or use an equivalent promotion, e.g.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] In the example above, we can materialize the conflict by adding a new table which makes the hidden constraint explicit, mapping each person to their *total balance*.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Phil would start off with a total balance of $200, and each transaction would attempt to subtract $200 from this, creating a write–write conflict that would prevent the two from succeeding concurrently.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] However, this approach violates the normal form.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Alternatively, we can promote one of the transaction's reads to a write.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] For instance, T2 could set V1 = V1, creating an artificial write–write conflict with T1 and, again, preventing the two from succeeding concurrently.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] This solution may not always be possible.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] In general, therefore, snapshot isolation puts some of the problem of maintaining non-trivial constraints onto the user, who may not appreciate either the potential pitfalls or the possible solutions.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] The upside to this transfer is better performance.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation is called "serializable" mode in Oracle and PostgreSQL versions prior to 9.1, which may cause confusion with the "real serializability" mode.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] There are arguments both for and against this decision; what is clear is that users must be aware of the distinction to avoid possible undesired anomalous behavior in their database system logic.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation arose from work on multiversion concurrency control databases, where multiple versions of the database are maintained concurrently to allow readers to execute without colliding with writers.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Such a system allows a natural definition and implementation of such an isolation level.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] InterBase, later owned by Borland, was acknowledged to provide SI rather than full serializability in version 4, and likely permitted write-skew anomalies since its first release in 1985.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Unfortunately, the ANSI SQL-92 standard was written with a lock-based database in mind, and hence is rather vague when applied to MVCC systems.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] Berenson *et al.* wrote a paper in 1995 critiquing the SQL standard, and cited snapshot isolation as an example of an isolation level that did not exhibit the standard anomalies described in the ANSI SQL-92 standard, yet still had anomalous behaviour when compared with serializable transactions.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] In 2008, Cahill *et al.* showed that write-skew anomalies could be prevented by detecting and aborting "dangerous" triplets of concurrent transactions.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] This implementation of serializability is well-suited to multiversion concurrency control databases, and has been adopted in PostgreSQL 9.1, where it is known as Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI).
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] When used consistently, this eliminates the need for the above workarounds.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] The downside over snapshot isolation is an increase in aborted transactions.
[src:apache-iceberg/snapshot-isolation] This can perform better or worse than snapshot isolation with the above workarounds, depending on workload.
